	<table cellpadding="1" cellspacing="0" border="0" bgcolor="#000000" width="470">
		<tr>
			<td>
				<table cellpadding="10" cellspacing="0" border="0" bgcolor="#FFFFCC" width="468">
					<tr>
						<td>
							<b>Game Development: What Works</b><br />
							The Game Development track exposes attendees to 
the game industry's most successful and 
influential designers and publishers. Hear first-
hand how designers create successful games, build 
and operate design studios, and work with 
publishers. Likewise, learn from publishers, what 
they look for in a game, what they expect from 
their development partners, and what creative 
risks they’re willing to assume.</td>
					</tr>
				</table>
			</td>
		</tr>
	</table>

	
	<p>	
	
		<b><a name="33"></a>4.1 - Hired Guns: The New Talent Pool and How to Fit In</b><br />
		Wednesday, May 14, 2003, 9:30 AM&nbsp;-&nbsp;11:00 AM<br />
		Room: 408B<br />
		&nbsp;<br />
		The game industry has always used freelance 
writers and musicians, but is increasingly 
turning to independent artists, designers, and 
producers for help as well. Is the Hollywood 
model of a large pool of freelance talent right 
for the games industry - or just inevitable?  
What should a publisher or developer consider 
when hiring freelance talent, and where can they 
find it? How does a talented freelancer best 
operate within this new structure? How do we as 
an industry borrow on the production disciplines 
from Hollywood to create a more sustainable (and 
predictable) growth curve? Come away from this 
session with a better understanding of how 
outside talent is changing the way games are 
produced, and how to manage your studio or 
publishing company to take advantage of this 
change.<br />
	
	</p>
		
	<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0">
	
	
	
	
	</table>
	
	
	
	&nbsp;<br />
	[ <a href="#top">Back to Top</a> ]
	&nbsp;<br clear="all" />

	
	<p>	
	
		<b><a name="34"></a>4.2 - Music Matters</b><br />
		Wednesday, May 14, 2003, 11:30 AM&nbsp;-&nbsp;1:00 PM<br />
		Room: 408B<br />
		&nbsp;<br />
		It's not just graphics and storyline that 
determine which games get talked about. More and 
more, it's the game's soundtrack that contributes 
to the splash it makes with the media, gamers, 
and retail. This panel will give attendees an 
understanding of how to use music to reach a 
specific, targeted demographic -- and will look 
at titles which successfully engaged gamers by 
the inclusion of top-quality music (think Tony 
Hawk and Grand Theft Auto). Learn how to match 
the right music with your game, how deals are 
structured, and how to find talent. The session 
will also address the reciprocal benefit record 
companies derive from their involvement in the 
game industry, how this relationship will likely 
grow, and how you can leverage the recording 
industry’s desire to ally with the game business.<br />
	
	</p>
		
	<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0">
	
	
	
	
	</table>
	
	
	
	&nbsp;<br />
	[ <a href="#top">Back to Top</a> ]
	&nbsp;<br clear="all" />

	
	<p>	
	
		<b><a name="35"></a>4.3 - Sneak Peeks: Taking the Wraps off the Hottest New Titles</b><br />
		Wednesday, May 14, 2003, 1:30 PM&nbsp;-&nbsp;3:00 PM<br />
		Room: 408B<br />
		&nbsp;<br />
		Last year’s Sneak Peeks session marked the first 
public demos of three of the industry’s most 
anticipated games: Doom III, C&C Generals, and 
Star Wars: Bounty Hunter. This year, we’ll get 
under the skin of three new games still in 
development. Learn how the top pros manage the 
game development process and hear how they juggle 
the needs of their team, their publisher, and the 
media. Always accompanied by playable code, Sneak 
Peeks is designed to inform by presenting a 
unique window into the game development process. 
Ask questions, take notes, and learn how the top 
designers handle the pressures of developing AAA 
product – and use that knowledge to make you own 
game development process that much more 
efficient. We will update the e3expo.com web site 
with more specifics as they are known. <br />
	
	</p>
		
	<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0">
	
	
	
	
	</table>
	
	
	
	&nbsp;<br />
	[ <a href="#top">Back to Top</a> ]
	&nbsp;<br clear="all" />

	
	<p>	
	
		<b><a name="36"></a>4.4 - Game AI Update: New Ways of Engaging the Player</b><br />
		Thursday, May 15, 2003, 9:00 AM&nbsp;-&nbsp;10:30 AM<br />
		Room: 408B<br />
		&nbsp;<br />
		Game AI is revitalizing the game industry, but 
not for reasons you might expect. The renaissance 
in game AI isn’t coming from increased technical 
capabilities or more sophisticated programming 
tools alone, but from the simple fact that 
designers are using AI and scripting with goals 
of entertaining gamers in new ways. This session 
will look at games which use AI in unique ways 
(such as Black & White, Grand Theft Auto, and 
Deus Ex). Learn from our panel of AI programmers 
as they discuss how they implemented AI and 
scripting language in their current games, what 
the market is responding to, and how they plan on 
using AI in their upcoming titles.<br />
	
	</p>
		
	<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0">
	
	
	
	
	</table>
	
	
	
	&nbsp;<br />
	[ <a href="#top">Back to Top</a> ]
	&nbsp;<br clear="all" />

	
	<p>	
	
		<b><a name="37"></a>4.5 - Tap the High-Tech Pulse of Gaming</b><br />
		Thursday, May 15, 2003, 11:00 AM&nbsp;-&nbsp;12:30 PM<br />
		Room: 408B<br />
		&nbsp;<br />
		Progress in ubiquitous gaming, adaptive audio, 
interactive music, and location-based games are 
just some areas where technology is influencing 
and sometimes changing the quality of game play. 
What is the status of these and other technical 
initiatives, in what ways are they changing game 
production and studio management, and is it time 
to address the technological challenge of 
transitioning to the next generation of consoles? 
Get up to speed on the most current high-tech 
development tools and learn how you can prepare 
your business enterprise for what lies ahead. <br />
	
	</p>
		
	<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0">
	
	
	
	
	</table>
	
	
	
	&nbsp;<br />
	[ <a href="#top">Back to Top</a> ]
	&nbsp;<br clear="all" />

	
	<p>	
	
		<b><a name="38"></a>4.6 - New Hooks in Gaming</b><br />
		Thursday, May 15, 2003, 2:00 PM&nbsp;-&nbsp;3:30 PM<br />
		Room: 408B<br />
		&nbsp;<br />
		What do The Sims, Grand Theft Auto, and Tony 
Hawk’s Pro Skater have in common? More than you 
think. Discover new ways game designers are using 
psychology, sociology, group dynamics, and 
artifacts of pop culture to make the new 
generation of games more appealing and rewarding 
to hardcore, casual, and neophyte gamers alike. 
Hear how the need for community, the power of 
freedom, and even the allure of rock ‘n’ roll are 
shaping a new generation of computer and video 
games.<br />
	
	</p>
		
